Carefully review the provided git diff and generate a user-focused MR/PR description written for a product or non-technical audience. Use this format:

### What's New?

[A clear, non-technical explanation of the new feature, improvement, or fix from a user's perspective. Derive this from the actual diff.]

### Why is This Important?

[Explain the user problem this change solves or the value it provides. Be specific to the diff — do not use generic placeholder text.]

### How It Works

[A brief walkthrough of the new or changed behaviour. Only include if there is a meaningful user-facing flow to describe; omit if the change is purely internal with no visible user impact.]

### Impact

[Describe the actual impact visible in the diff. Only include bullet points that apply — omit any that are not relevant to this change. Never output placeholder text like "[How this change will affect users]".]

Formatting rules:
- Use plain language accessible to non-technical readers
- Only include sections with content derived from the actual diff
- Never output placeholder text like "N/A", "[Description]", or "[How this change will affect users]"
- Output only the description body — no title line, no preamble

The git diff may be truncated – focus analysis on visible changes.
